{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 19:23:44.546611", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nTopology and scope\\n- Fabric: 1 spine (spine_1) and 2 leaves (leaf_1, leaf_2)\\n- Hosts: host_1_1(10.0.0.1), host_1_2(10.0.0.2) on leaf_1; host_2_1(10.0.0.5), host_2_2(10.0.0.6) on leaf_2\\n- Controller: tcp:20.0.0.100:6633, all OVS bridges are connected, fail_mode: secure\\n\\n1) Anomaly detection (symptoms)\\n- End-to-end reachability is broken, including on the same leaf:\\n  - host_1_2 -> host_1_1: Destination Host Unreachable (local host 10.0.0.2)\\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2: command times out\\n  - host_1_1/host_1_2 -> host_2_1/host_2_2: Destination Host Unreachable or timeout\\n  - host_2_1 -> host_2_2: Destination Host Unreachable\\n- ARP resolution failures:\\n  - ip neigh shows FAILED for 10.0.0.6 on multiple hosts; 10.0.0.1 and 10.0.0.2 lack valid neighbor entries for each other when tested\\n- Host interface counters show very low TX and relatively high RX (e.g., host_1_1 RX ~40k pkts vs TX 30 pkts), consistent with switches sending traffic to hosts but hosts’ outbound frames not being forwarded correctly\\n\\n2) Localization (fault domain and devices)\\nData-plane behavior on leaf_1 and leaf_2 is incorrect as programmed by the controller:\\n\\n- Hairpin (self-forwarding) rules on access ports:\\n  - leaf_1: flow installs in_port=1 actions=output:1 (n_packets=30), which loops frames received from host_1_1 (eth0) back to the same port instead of switching to peers/uplinks\\n  - leaf_2: flow installs in_port=2 actions=output:2 (n_packets=18), looping frames from host_2_2 (eth1) back to itself\\n  These hairpin rules explain why host_1_1 and host_2_2 cannot talk to anyone (their traffic is not forwarded off their access ports), and why ARP fails.\\n\\n- Missing or incomplete host-specific flows:\\n  - No flows observed matching the MACs of host_1_1 (f2:8a:85:15:de:06) and host_2_2 (ce:18:16:18:99:6e)\\n  - Some flows exist for host_1_2 (7e:19:8d:76:c2:be) and host_2_1 (ba:04:49:03:4d:43), but they are paired with questionable egress ports (see below)\\n\\n- Wrong uplink/egress port selection on leaves:\\n  - On leaf_1, flows destined to host_2_1 (dl_dst=ba:04:49:03:4d:43) output to port 5 (eth4), and many other flows steer to ports 5/6 (eth4/eth5)\\n  - On leaf_2, similarly heavy use of ports 5/6 for fabric traffic\\n  - Topology states leaf uplinks to spine_1 are eth2 and eth3; eth4 and eth5 are not specified as data-plane links\\n  - Port statistics corroborate the mismatch: leaf_1/leaf_2 ports 5/6 carry large volumes; ports 3/4 (the defined uplinks) show comparatively low RX, indicating the controller is steering traffic into the wrong (non-topology) ports\\n\\n- Spine_1 is connected and has traffic on ports 1/2/3 (consistent with its three leaf links), but its flow entries also reference unexpected MACs and are aligned with the controller’s programming; there is no evidence spine_1 itself is the source of the error—rather it’s receiving a faulty policy.\\n\\n3) Root cause analysis\\n- Control-plane misprogramming by the SDN controller (20.0.0.100) is causing:\\n  - Installation of hairpin rules on leaf access ports (in_port -> same output), which traps traffic from host_1_1 and host_2_2 on their own ports and breaks ARP and L2 switching locally\\n  - Incorrect egress port mapping on leaves, steering inter-leaf traffic to eth4/eth5 instead of the actual uplinks (eth2/eth3) defined by the physical topology\\n  - Missing flows for certain host MACs (host_1_1 and host_2_2), which in secure fail_mode results in drops for unknown unicast/ARP broadcasts\\n- With fail_mode=secure and no proper table-miss/ARP flood handling, any traffic lacking explicit match-action entries is dropped, compounding the connectivity failures.\\n\\nKey supporting evidence\\n- Pings: consistent Destination Host Unreachable/timeouts even on same leaf\\n- ARP: FAILED entries for peers, absence of valid neighbors\\n- OVS flows:\\n  - leaf_1: cookie=0x0, table=0, in_port=1 actions=output:1; no flows for f2:8a:85:15:de:06\\n  - leaf_2: cookie=0x0, table=0, in_port=2 actions=output:2; no flows for ce:18:16:18:99:6e\\n  - Multiple flows sending to output:5/6 (eth4/eth5) instead of actual uplinks\\n- OVS port stats:\\n  - leaf_1: ports 5/6 carry the majority of RX/TX; uplinks 3/4 show little RX\\n  - leaf_2: same pattern\\n- Switch–controller: is_connected: true on all switches; thus not a connectivity loss to controller, but a policy/topology mapping error\\n\\nAssessment of network health\\n- Health: Critically degraded. L2 connectivity is broken for multiple hosts (including intra-leaf), ARP resolution fails, and inter-leaf forwarding is steered to incorrect ports.\\n- Faulty devices: Data-plane symptoms manifest on leaf_1 and leaf_2 (due to installed flows), with spine_1 participating per the controller’s programming.\\n- Root cause: Misconfiguration/bug in the SDN controller’s topology/port mapping and host learning logic leading to hairpin flows, wrong uplink selection, and missing host flows under secure fail mode., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='dbdc1b47-5e97-400f-9773-0af23ece7950'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
